{{Infobox games | name = FIS Alpine World Ski Championships 2019 | logo = | size = | caption = | host city = [[Åre]] | country = [[Sweden]] | motto = | nations participating = | teams participating = | debuting countries = | athletes participating = | events = 11 | opening ceremony = {{start date|2019|2|5|df=y}} | closing ceremony = {{end date|2019|2|17|df=y}} | officially opened by = | stadium = | website = [http://are2019.com/ are2019.com] | previous = [[FIS Alpine World Ski Championships 2017|Saint Moritz 2017]] | next = [[FIS Alpine World Ski Championships 2021|Cortina d'Ampezzo 2021]] }} {{Location map |Europe |relief = 1 |label = <small>Åre</small> |lat = 63.415 |long = 13.062 |caption = Location in [[Europe]] |position = |marksize = 5 |float = |background = |width = 240 }} {{Location map |Sweden |relief = 1 |label = <small>Åre</small> |lat = 63.415 |long = 13.062 |caption = Location in [[Sweden]] |position = |marksize = 5 |float = |background = |width = 130 }} The '''FIS Alpine World Ski Championships 2019''' are scheduled for 5–17 February in [[Åre ski resort|Åre]], [[Sweden]]. The host city was selected at the [[International Ski Federation|FIS]] Congress in [[Barcelona]], [[Spain]], on 5 June 2014. The only other applicant was [[Cortina d'Ampezzo]], [[Italy]],<ref>[http://skiracing.com/stories/are-sweden-selected-to-host-2019-world-alpine-ski-champs/ Åre, Sweden selected to host 2019 World Alpine Ski Champs.]</ref> which later gained the 2021 championships.
Åre previously hosted the [[FIS Alpine World Ski Championships|world championships]] in [[FIS Alpine World Ski Championships 1954|1954]] and [[FIS Alpine World Ski Championships 2007|2007]], and has held numerous [[FIS Alpine Ski World Cup|World Cup]] events.
